Your current workflow = k-means representatives (≈90%) + k-center greedy tail (≈10%)

This is a strong, practical hybrid: balances density (typical cases) and coverage (edge cases)

Main weakness: the 90:10 split is arbitrary and should be tuned or benchmarked

You explored replacing it with p-median / p-center / MCLP

These methods natively operate on pairwise distance matrices (n×n)

They support any distance (geostatistical, energy, EMD, etc.) — no Euclidean assumption

They also handle “legacy” / preselected points cleanly (major advantage)

Conceptually:

p-median ≈ representativeness (like k-means stage)

p-center ≈ coverage (like k-center stage)

Your hybrid already approximates both objectives

Key tradeoff:

Facility-location methods = more principled but more expensive (NP-hard)

Require full distance matrix → memory + compute bottleneck

Best architecture:

Use your current hybrid to compress data (e.g., 50k → 2k)

Apply p-median / p-center on reduced set with custom distance

Recommendation:

Keep current method as baseline

Add greedy p-median as comparator / refinement

Evaluate using metrics: mean / p90 / max nearest distance

Bottom line:
👉 Your workflow is solid and likely competitive
👉 Facility-location methods are best used as a second-stage optimizer, not full replacement